Happy, truly, is the naturalist. He has no time for melancholy dreams. The earth be- comes to him transparent ; everywhere he sees sig- nificances, harmonies, laws, chains of cause and effect endlessly interlinked, which draw him out of the narrow sphere of sels-interest and sels-pleas- ing into a pure and wholesome region of solemn joy and wonder.”

We must here conclude our remarks on Science. To discuss the characteristic features of the in- ductive and deductive philosophy throughout, would be beside our present purpose. We are content with having endeavoured to disclose a more comprehensive view of scienee, than the youth of seventeen is commonly by himself enabled to take. To have attempted to define 3 course of scientific study, or to speak with greater distinct- ness of any one of the sciences, would have been to sacrifice our design of furnishing a review of scientific method in general. Any one being in earnest about the adoption of 3 particular branch of study, will find abundant store of special assist- ance ready to his hand.
